I walked into this place around 10:40 PM last night and the waitstaff told me that the kitchen was closed. I asked them what time the kitchen closes and they told me 10:30 PM. I returned tonight, a Saturday, at 10:08 PM and a waiter again told me that the restaurant was closed. I explained that less than 24 hours earlier I was told the kitchen closes at 10:30 PM. He explained that it wasn’t that busy so they shut everything down early. He wasn’t especially sympathetic either, walking backwards as I spoke to him and eager to turn away altogether. I hate when restaurants close early. All restaurants should be required to (a) clearly advertise their hours of business—or explicitly state that they reserve the right to close whenever they decide, for any reason—and (b) stay open until the advertised closing time. I understand thst business is slow sometimes, but that should be part of the cost of doing business. I think of the advertised closing time as a contract with customer. If things are always slow after 10 PM, then perhaps advertised closing time should be 10 PM. Customers will never get upset if, on busy nights, a restaurant extends its hours beyond its advertised closing tine; however, some customers may stop patronizing a restaurant when they realize can’t rely on it to honor its advertised closing time.
